meta.TITLE: THROMBOSED POPLITEAL ANEURYSM
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Admitted to hospital with gangrene of the left foot.  A non-pulsative mass could be felt in the popliteal fossa.  Femoral pulse was papable on affected side, but no pulses could be felt below this.  An above knee amputation was performed.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A coronal section has been cut through the flexed knee passing posterior to the knee joint.  The femur is seen cut in cross section and immediately below it a cross section of a thrombosed fusiform aneurysm of the popliteal artery.  The thrombosed vessel visible below it is the popliteal vein.  A larger diameter of the aneurysm is visible on the posterior surface of the specimen.

meta.TITLE: SURGICAL ARTERIAL RECONSTRUCTION
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Symptoms and signs of progressive ischaemia of both legs were investigated by arteriography and he was found to have complete obstruction of the left external iliac artery and gross narrowing of the right external iliac.  The peripheral arteries were in reasonable condition.  An operation was performed in which a plastic prosthesis was inserted between the aorta and the femoral arteries.  Postoperative course was uneventful and there was considerable improvement to the blood flow to the legs with complete loss of symptoms.  Nine months after operation he died from a cardiac infarction.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The aorta showing the prosthesis as found at autopsy.  It was fully patent and there was no thrombus present.  Note the fibrous capsule that has formed round the prosthesis (it had contracted away from it during fixation).  The obstructed left iliac artery can be seen lying inside the line of the prosthesis on that side.

meta.TITLE: AORTA
meta.SUBTITLE: ANEURYSMAL DILATION
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: An elderly man who died of a massive cerebral infarction.  He had generalized atherosclerosis of all major arteries.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The heart and thoracic aorta showing dilation of the arch and upper part of the descending aorta.  The wall shows extensive complicated atheromatous plaques and there are large areas of adherent mural thrombus.  Thrombus is also present in the right common carotid artery.  The aortic valve is normal.  The left ventricular myocardium is thickened probably due to hypertrophy associated with hypertension.  The aortic valve is normal.  The left ventricular myocardium is thickened probably due to hypertrophy associated with hypertension.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Histological section showed atherosclerosis only with no evidence of syphilitic aortitis (syphilitic aortitis often produces a diffuse aneurysmal dilation of this type).

meta.TITLE: DISSECTING ANEURYSM OF AORTA
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: This patient had been known to have severe calcific aortic stenosis for a number of years.  She had had episodes of left ventricular failure but these had been controlled by standard medical treatment.  She was admitted to hospital following an episode of chest pain that was thought to be of cardiac origin.  She recovered rapidly after admission and there was no ECG evidence of myocardial infarction and no rise in CK levels.  She was discharged.  She was admitted again one week later following collapse and severe chest pain, again there was no evidence of myocardial infarction.  12 hours after admission she collapsed again and could not be resuscitated.  At autopsy she was found to have a bicuspid aortic valve with severe calcific stenosis, dissecting aneurysm of the aorta and a massive mediastinal haemorrhage.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Part of the heart and the ascending aorta with the anterior wall of the aorta removed.  The dissection of the aortic wall and the haemorrhage into the mediastinal tissues is clearly demonstrated.  There are two entry tears in the intima of the aorta and the appearances suggest that this patient had two separate episodes of dissection.  One horizontal tear is seen in the left lateral wall of the aorta 4-cm above the aortic valve.  The related thrombus in the adjacent area of dissection is relatively old.  This could have been responsible for the first episode of chest pain. The second tear is V-shaped in the right lateral wall of the aorta 2 cm above the aortic valve.  It can just be seen through the front of the specimen box but is more clearly visible on looking down through the top of the box.  The haemorrhage in relation to this tear is fresh and was the source of the massive mediastinal haemorrhage, which was the immediate cause of death.

meta.TITLE: DISSECTING ANEURYSM OF AORTA
meta.SUBTITLE: MEDIONECROSIS
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Sudden pain in the chest radiating to the back and neck. Collapsed some hours later.  Died four hours after admission in peripheral circulatory failure.  No history of hypertension.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Longitudinal split in the aortic intima is shown.  The dissection had extended down to the coeliac axis artery. Rupture had occurred into the pericardial cavity.

meta.TITLE: ABDOMINAL AORTA
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: 44.48.04, 44.48.05 , 44.48.06, 44.48.07: Abdominal aortas from different age groups stained to display fatty deposits.

meta.TITLE: AORTA
meta.SUBTITLE: ATHEROMA
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: A 50 year old man who was severely injured in a road accident and died of his injuries 24 hours later.  No significant disease found at autopsy apart from atheroma.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The abdominal aorta and iliac arteries showing a moderate degree of "complicated" atheroma.  In the upper abdominal aorta and in the iliac arteries there are fibrous and fatty intimal plaques present.  In the lower abdominal aorta and at the bifurcation there are ulcerated plaques with associated calcification.  Note the rigidity of the lower part shown by the way it holds its shape in contrast to the rest of the specimen.

meta.TITLE: HEART AND AORTA
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The specimen shows an atherosclerotic aneurysm of the aorta just distal to the aortic valve. At the posterior aspect there is a 2-cm site of rupture.  Death owing to rupture of an atherosclerotic aneurysm of the ascending aorta with cardiac tamponade.
